			<div class="content" id="post-content-3890757">
									

<p>While I did upvote this, there is something that is really giving me a head ache while I'm reading this.</p>
<p>I found something a little confusing. Atleast, maybe it's a clear, but I feel like I'm missing it. How exactly did they figure out that the movie was sent to the past and is in a time loop? Was it because the Foundation, at the time that the email was sent, finally received the technology to be able to send things into the past? And then again, how would the Foundation know that THEY were the ones involved in sending it to the past?</p>
<p>That, and most of the stories I've read involving the bootstrap paradox<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-176116-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-176116-1')">1</a></sup> usually has the people within the loop <strong>unaware</strong> that they're in a loop in the in the first place, therefore it makes sense for the object in question to be what keeps getting sent back in time. So my question is, how would the Foundation know <em>when</em> they are supposed to send the movie back in time? And why would they send back a movie of all things and not just a note saying <em>&quot;Hey Foundation, time travel is possible&quot;</em>.</p>
<p>All in all not bad, I just feel like a few things don't really add up here. It's teetering on no-vote territory for me, but the Foundation making the past Foundation aware of time travel is a cool concept to me.</p>
